Basically what I’ve done is, I built a single reconciliation table where I’m comparing the CSV data we receive from Athena against the MQS flow, and also doing the reverse — so flow against CSV — but both results are stored in the same table with a direction flag.

The way the matching works is pretty straightforward — I’m not using timestamps for joining. I’m only matching based on business keys, so interactionId, mqsQuoteId, and transactionCode. Once I find a match on those, then I compare the timestamps separately.

So for every matched pair, I calculate the time difference between the CSV request timestamp and the MQS enqueued time — I store that as diff in minutes, hours, days, and also absolute hours. That gives us flexibility later to derive SLA or delays in reporting rather than hardcoding it in the pipeline.

If there are multiple matches in MQS for the same record, I just pick the closest one based on timestamp difference — so we always get the nearest event.

For records that don’t match initially, I don’t mark them permanently missing. Instead, I recheck them in subsequent runs. The idea is that data might arrive late in the flow, so every run looks back within a ±15-day window to see if the record has appeared. If it shows up later, it gets updated from missing to matched.

And similarly for reverse — if something exists in the flow but not in the CSV, it gets flagged as missing in CSV, but that can also get resolved in a later run if the CSV picks it up.

So overall, the table just stores the raw comparison — match or no match and the time difference — and all the reconciliation percentages and SLA logic are derived later in reporting. Keeps the pipeline simple and flexible.
